<br>
    Past a professional job, specific tasks that require communication and interaction should have a common basis. It's one thing for someone who is not a native speaker of English to come here, make a thorough argument, and have some grammatical (&lt;---crap, that's not a real word, is it?) errors. It is another for someone who should be well enough versed in the English language to be coherent to come here and post drivel. They are entitled to, most definitely, but with all things being equal their words will not be given as much credence based on the presentation they are given. They don't have to spell everything perfectly or get every grammer rule just right - nobody I know does - but the effort to try to will be evident in a more fluid and persuasive post. Presentation isn't just a tool for high powered coorporate meetings, it is also a tool used in every day life and situations - like when you decide whether or not to give spare change to a homeless person based on how much they smell like beer, or when you're standing in line at McDonalds trying to order a number 5 but you're speaking gibberish the guy behind the counter can't understand. EQ is no exception, in game or on the boards.<br>
<br>
-Astos<br>
